SIMPLE: trouble
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trouble
<hw>Trou"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Troubled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Troubling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>troubler</ets>, OF. <ets>trobler</ets>, <ets>trubler</ets>,
<ets>tourbler</ets>,fr. (assumed) LL. <ets>turbulare</ets>, L.
<ets>turbare</ets> to disorderly group, a little crowd; both from
<ets>turba</ets> a disorder, tumult, crowd; akin to Gr. <?/, and perhaps
to E. <ets>thorp</ets>; cf. Skr. <ets>tvar</ets>, <ets>tur</ets>,o
hasten. Cf. <er>Turbid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put into
confused motion; to disturb; to agitate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An angel went down at a certain season into the pool, and
<qex>troubled</qex> the water.</q> <rj><qau>John v. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God looking forth will <qex>trouble</qex> all his host.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To disturb; to perplex; to afflict; to distress; to
grieve; to fret; to annoy; to vex.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now is my soul <qex>troubled</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>John xii.
27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take the boy to you; he so <qex>troubles</qex> me⟦br⟧
'T is past enduring.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Never <qex>trouble</qex> yourself about those faults which age
will cure.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To give occasion for labor to; -- used in polite
phraseology; <as>as, I will not <ex>trouble</ex> you to deliver the
letter</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To disturb; perplex; afflict; distress; grieve;
harass; annoy; tease; vex; molest.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trouble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trouble
<hw>Trou"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Troubled; dark;
gloomy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧With full <xex>trouble</xex>
cheer.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trouble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trouble
<hw>Trou"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>trouble</ets>, OF.
<ets>troble</ets>, <ets>truble</ets>. See <er>Trouble</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being troubled;
disturbance; agitation; uneasiness; vexation; calamity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest the fiend . . . some new <qex>trouble raise</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Foul whisperings are abroad; unnatural deeds⟦br⟧
Do breed unnatural <qex>troubles</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which gives disturbance, annoyance, or
vexation; that which afflicts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A fault or interruption in a
stratum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To get into trouble</b></col>, <cd>to get into difficulty
or danger.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To take the
trouble</b></col>, <cd>to be at the pains; to exert one's self; to give
one's self inconvenience.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She never <qex>took the trouble</qex> to close them.</q>
<rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Affliction; disturbance; perplexity; annoyance;
molestation; vexation; inconvenience; calamity; misfortune; adversity;
embarrassment; anxiety; sorrow; misery.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troubler</ent>⟦br⟧
